     <int-org-section id="IO-UN.1677" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Finance</heading>
          <p>
      UNRWA is financed almost entirely by voluntary contributions from governments and the European Union (EU), the remainder being provided by UN bodies, non-governmental organizations, business corporations and private sources, which also contribute to extra-budgetary activities. Successive crises have long placed extreme pressure on the Agency’s resources, and reduced funding for priority initiatives (for example rehabilitation projects resulting from conflict). Following a Pledging Conference for UNRWA that was convened in June 2023 by the President of the UN General Assembly, at which US $828.3m. was pledged, the Agency’s Commissioner-General warned that the funding thus far received would be insufficient adequately to sustain operations. In January 2024 several donor nations paused additional funding allocations to UNRWA, pending a review of the allegations levelled by Israel of involvement by 12 Agency personnel in the atrocities perpetrated by Hamas on 7 October 2023 (see 
      <i>Gaza and the West Bank</i>
      ).
    </p>
          <p usage="mena">In March 2019 the UNRWA Commissioner-General welcomed a decision by the Organization of Islamic Cooperation to establish a new Waqf (endowment) Fund to Support Palestine Refugees. </p>
